\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.2 Eradication Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The IC holds authority over all eradication activity.
 No eradication action shall be initiated without IC authorization.
 The IC shall select the applicable eradication procedures,
 assign technical leads,
 and direct the sequence and timing of eradication actions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Before eradication execution begins,
 the IC shall confirm the scope of eradication based on the containment perimeter and the incident classification established in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:4.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
.
 The IC shall document the eradication scope in the work order Notes before execution begins.
 The eradication scope shall identify:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
All systems within the containment perimeter requiring remediation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The specific threat artifacts and persistence mechanisms to be removed from each system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
The applicable eradication procedures to be invoked.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
Any systems where the eradication approach requires a destructive action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Eradication actions fall into three (3) categories,
 distinguished by reversibility and forensic impact.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Non-Destructive Eradication:

\series default
 Actions that remove threat artifacts without altering the underlying system's ability to be forensically examined after the fact.
 Examples include deleting malware files,
 removing unauthorized scheduled tasks or services,
 closing unauthorized network connections,
 and revoking compromised authentication tokens.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Credential and Access Remediation:

\series default
 Actions that revoke,
 rotate,
 or replace compromised authentication credentials and access authorizations.
 Examples include password resets,
 certificate revocation,
 API key rotation,
 and disabling compromised accounts.
 These actions are operationally reversible but may disrupt active authentication sessions for the affected accounts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
\lang english
Destructive Eradication:

\series default
 Actions that alter or destroy system state in a manner that cannot be reversed and that may eliminate forensic evidence if not preceded by preservation.
 Examples include reimaging a compromised endpoint,
 rebuilding a server from clean media,
 wiping and redeploying a virtual machine,
 and overwriting compromised storage volumes.
 Destructive Eradication actions require the Forensic Preservation Gate defined in Section 6.3 to be satisfied before execution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Eradication owns everything required to neutralize the threat and confirm clean state.
 Recovery owns everything required to restore operational capability.
 A system rebuild is eradication when it is performed because the system cannot be confirmed clean.
 A system rebuild is recovery when the system is confirmed clean and is being rebuilt to restore service.
 The eradication-complete determination in Section 6.4 marks this boundary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For incidents where Criminal Justice Information (CJI) involvement is confirmed or has not been ruled out at triage,
 the IC shall ensure the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\lang english
